@NODE INTRODUCTION "SongPlayerCLI - Introduction"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   Introduction@{UB}

   This utility is a simple means of controlling SongPlayer via the CLI
   (or Shell). If you have SongPlayer installed on your system, then you
   can use this utility straight after installation. If however you do
   not have SongPlayer, you will have to install it. It can be found on
   most recent Amiga Format CD-ROMs, and on AmiNET.

   SongPlayer by Stephane TAVENARD is a powerful utility for playing sound
   files, and supports most sound formats. This utility is designed to help
   you play MP3s (MPEG1-III) in your playlist, but can be used to play 
   any sound files in the playlist.

   After installation, you can then control your version of SongPlayer via
   the CLI interface, be it one you have started from Workbench, or the
   standard AmigaDOS window you get when you boot with no startup sequence
   (this is the intended use). 

   I hope you find this utility useful. I know I do! I am always booting
   from no startup sequence, because I am starting to like the CLI more
   than my Magellan 2 Workbench!! (shock! horror!)
  
   Gareth Griffiths.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ABOUT_THE_AUTHOR "SongPlayerCLI - About The Author"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   About The Author@{UB}

   Well, I'm 16 years old, and I live in Shrewsbury in the UK. There is 
   a photograph of me in the archive, named Author.jpg (it is a JPEG file
   so you will need a suitable viewer to look at it) and whilst I may not
   be the best looking guy in the world, it don't matter, 'cos looks don't
   mean shit, it's personality that counts in my book!! And everyone tells
   me that I have a great one of those, with a good sense of humour etc.
   etc. Indeed, some people even think I have a sexy voice!!! :o)

   I got my first Amiga (the A1200 I have now) in 1994, and started
   upgrading it in 1996. The first upgrade was a 772Mb hard drive and an
   8Mb RAM board, from Gasteiner. The 8Mb RAM was soon limiting however,
   so I persuaded a mate to buy me a 68030 accelerator board from Eyetech. 
   It came with two SIMM sockets, so I filled them up with 8Mb each, giving
   me 16Mb RAM. Nice!! 

   However, the power of the '030 wasn't enough either, so earlier this 
   year I upgraded to a Blizzard 1260 Turbo board. The 68060 processor is
   shit-hot and my Amiga is faster than ever. And I like it!!!

   I still have the 16Mb RAM, although I am trying to find a 32Mb SIMM for
   cheap. My next upgrade will probably be a tower followed by a PPC board.
   Then I will get a graphics card, so that I can view large files without
   Workbench taking up all of my fucking Chip RAM :o(

   *  Apologies for any bad language in this documentation file. I could
      easily edit it out, but what the fuck happened to free speech? :o)

   *  If you want to contact me, e.mail me at kgrandpa@yahoo.com

@ENDNODE

