@NODE REQUIREMENTS "SongPlayerCLI - Requirements"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   Requirements@{UB}

   To make good use of the SongPlayer CLI Controller you will need:-

      À  An Amiga (durrrrr)

      À  A version of Workbench with RexxMast installed and running.
      
      À  rexxreqtools.library in your LIBS: directory (not included)
         Search for RexxReqTools.lha on Aminet. It should be in util/rexx

      À  Magic User Interface (not actually needed for this, but 
         SongPlayer itself uses it.)

      À  SongPlayer (only tested on v1.53, send me your version if it
         works!)

      À  A Shell/CLI (should have come either in ROM or with Workbench)

      À  Some sound files/playlists to use it with!!!

   A mouse isn't particularly required unless you want to control
   SongPlayer with it, but that would defeat the object of using this
   program, would it not?

@ENDNODE 

@NODE INSTALLATION "SongPlayerCLI - Installation"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   Installation@{UB}

   At the moment it is only possible to install the CLI controller manually
   but I am busy working on an Installer script to do the job for you.
   keep an eye open for updates!

   To install the software manually, follow these instructions:-

      À  Copy all files from the Rexx directory of the archive into your
               REXX: assign. Keep the SpCLI directory structure!!. 

      À  Copy these files somewhere into your system path (C: is good):-

            À  RunSongPlayer
            À  SpCLI
      
      À  Edit the RunSongPlayer text file so that it points to your
         SongPlayer executable. For example, by default the file contains:-

            Run >NIL: C:SongPlayer

         But if your SongPlayer was contained in Tools: you would change it to:-

            Run >NIL: Tools:SongPlayer

         And then save the file and exit.

      À  If they are not already set, make sure both the files have their
         S protection bit set. To do this, go to a CLI window and type:-

            Protect RunSongPlayer +SRWED <RETURN>
            Protect SpCLI +SRWED <RETURN>

      À  Installation complete! See the @{"Usage" LINK Usage} section now!

@ENDNODE

@NODE USAGE "SongPlayerCLI - Usage"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   Usage@{UB}

   Making use of the program couldn't be simpler. The 'SpCLI' file you 
   copied during installation is the core of the program. Go to a CLI
   and type 'SpCLI help' and you should be presented with a list of the
   commands.

   Here is the list of commands (some are linked, as they need further
   explanation):-

       PLAY        - Plays the current file.
       STOP        - Stops the current file.

      @{" ADD      " LINK CMD_Add}  - Adds a file to the playlist.
       FIRST       - Selects the first file in the playlist.
       PREV        - Selects the previous file in the playlist.
       NEXT        - Selects the next file in the playlist.
       LAST        - Selects the last file in the playlist.
       RANDOM      - Selects a random file from the playlist.
      @{" SELECT   " LINK CMD_Select}  - Allows you to select a file based on its ID.
      @{" FIND     " LINK CMD_Find}  - Prompts you for a search string to find a title.

       COUNT       - Counts the number of files in the playlist.
       INFO        - Gives information on the current file.
       LIST        - Outputs a list of all files in the playlist.

       SHOW        - Shows the SongPlayer interface.
       HIDE        - Hides the SongPlayer interface.
       QUIT        - Exits SongPlayer completely.

      @{" HELP     " LINK CMD_Help}  - Displays the help text.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CMD_Add "SongPlayerCLI - Add"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   Command: ADD <path>@{UB}

     The ADD command allows you to add new files to the end of the current
     playlist.

     You can either enter the filepath directly in the command, or leave
     it blank and a file requester will pop up.

     For example, I could type:
     
          SpCLI ADD DH3:Music/LockNLoad_BlowYaMind.mp3

     And then that file would be added to the end of the playlist, and
     SongPlayer would automatically play it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CMD_Select "SongPlayerCLI - Select"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   Command: SELECT <id>@{UB}

   This command enables you to select a specific file in the playlist.
   Pass the ID number as parameter <id> and it will automatically jump
   to that file. If you leave <id> blank, you are prompted.

   But how do I get the ID numbers???

   Simple! There are two commands that give out ID numbers, LIST and @{"FIND" LINK CMD_Find}.
   LIST just outputs a list of all of the files in the playlist, preceded
   by a number. For example:-

      @{B}À  (1) Travis: Turn
      À  (2) Alice Deejay: Back In My Life
      À  (3) Eminem: Brain Damage
      (etc. etc.)@{UB}

   So, if you wanted to select 'Brain Damage' as the file to play, you would
   enter '3' at the prompt (minus the quotes) Like so:-
   
      @{B}Enter ID Number: 3
      Current File: (3) Eminem: Brain Damage@{UB}

   There ya go! @{"FIND" LINK CMD_Find} does much the same thing, but allows
   for more specific searches. See its page for more information.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CMD_Find "SongPlayerCLI - Find"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   Command: FIND <string>@{UB}

   The FIND command allows you to search through the TITLES of your playlist
   files for a specified string. You can either pass this string directly
   as a parameter, e.g.:
   
      SpCLI FIND "Brain"   - don't forget those quotes!
      
   or you can leave it blank and the program will prompt you for a search
   string. Using the "Brain" example above, if my playlist looked like this:

      @{B}À  (1) Travis: Turn
      À  (2) Alice Deejay: Back In My Life
      À  (3) Eminem: Brain Damage
      À  (4) Wamdue Project: King Of My Castle
      À  (5) REM: Shiny Happy People
      À  (6) Lou Bega: Mambo Number Five
      À  (7) The Prodigy: Smack My Bitch Up
      À  (8) Eminem: Just Don't Give A Fuck
      À  (9) New Order: 1963@{UB}

   I would get this back in return:
      
         @{B}À  (3) Eminem: Brain Damage
      1 matche(s) found.@{UB} 

   Enabling me to use the @{"SELECT" LINK CMD_Select} command to jump 
   straight to that file! 

   Note that it does not search for whole words, it searches for occurences,
   so if I typed my search string as 'm' I would get this:-

      @{B}Enter search string: m
      
         À  (2) Alice Deejay: Back In My Life
         À  (3) Eminem: Brain Damage
         À  (4) Wamdue Project: King Of My Castle
         À  (6) Lou Bega: Mambo Number Five
         À  (7) The Prodigy: Smack My Bitch Up
      5 matche(s) found.@{UB}

   Simple huh? :o)

@ENDNODE

@NODE CMD_Help "SongPlayerCLI - Help"

   @{B}SongPlayerCLI.
   Version 1.52 (16-04-2000)
   By Gareth Griffiths (gazchap@btinternet.com)


   Command: HELP <command>@{UB}

   This command gives you instant help on any command used by SpCLI. You
   can pass the command you are needing help with as a parameter, e.g:
   
      SpCLI HELP SELECT
      
   Which will display the help text for the SELECT command.
   
   Alternatively, you can leave <command> blank and a general help text
   will be displayed, containing brief help on all the commands.
   
@ENDNODE

